column1: What will voter turnout be in the 2022 presidency elections in Bosnia and Herzegovina (Bosnia)?
column5: ['Less than 44.0%', 'Between 44.0% and 48.0%, inclusive', 'More than 48.0% but less than 52.0%', 'Between 52.0% and 56.0%, inclusive', 'More than 56.0%', 'Presidency elections will not be held in 2022']

column6: Historical voter turnout is high ~60%! But I'm guessing this election will be less than usual due to the myriad post-pandemic mindset plus war resource shortages making it harder for folks to reach the polls.
Extremization of the consensus view while sticking with the base rate idea that the election turnout is around 54%.

High tensions in the region, and boycott threats will most likely detract from election turnout, but previous numbers and determined voters will most likely still result in a substantial turnout around the 50% mark. Especially with the way candidates are selected dependent on being a Serb, Croat, or Bosnian, members of each group will most likely be especially galvanized to turn out to lend their support via ballot.
New articles suggest this election will be entirely unexceptional, so I'm going with the usual turnout numbers.

There seems to be nothing in the news about elections not being held. In fact, the news cycle seems to support that this year will be a pretty typical election year, and in those years voter turnout is somewhere between 52% and 56%.

I'll be honest, I am mostly just going with the wisdom of the crowd here, but there is also some thought. In the past few presidential elections, voter turnout has been around 54%-56%. While there are some hot button issues being represented this year, such as the electoral reform that could draw out more voters, I think that the general disorder that is accompanying this election such as the budget issues will roughly balance this out. I can easily foresee putting a greater percentage value in a higher percentage category in the coming days.
The past few elections have had fairly consistent turnouts at ~53%.
